	<Language_en_US>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_3UC_TIMBERLINE_LODGE">
			<Text>Timberline Lodge</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_3UC_TIMBERLINE_LODGE_STRATEGY">
			<Text>The Timberline Lodge is a unique national wonder to Oregon that greatly increases the [ICON_GOLD] Gold of a city. Unlike the National Epic it replaces, the Timberline Lodge boosts production of armored and naval units in the city, and [ICON_RES_IRON] Iron and [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal tiles yield +2 [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production. [NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Requires 1 [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_3UC_TIMBERLINE_LODGE_HELP">
			<Text>Increases the [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production of a city. Boosts production of armored and naval units. [ICON_RES_IRON] Iron and [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal tiles yield +2 [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production. Only America may built it.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Requires 1 [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CIV5_BUILDINGS_3UC_TIMBERLINE_LODGE_TEXT">
			<Text>The Timberline Lodge is a mountain lodge constructed on the side of Mt. Hood constructed from 1936 to 1938.  Timberline Lodge was dedicated September 28, 1937, by President Franklin D. Roosevelt.  The lodge draws 2 million vistors anually and is a popular tourist attraction of Oregon.  The outside of the lodge has been popularized by a variety of famous american films, including
			The Shining by Stanley Kubrick.  In 1942, it was closed due to disrepair.  It remained closed for over 18 years, but re-opened in 1960 due to explosive popularity over skiiing.  Today, it is a major landmark of the land.</Text>
		</Row>
	</Language_en_US>

